external_knowledge:
- "encoding scenarios" refer to specific contexts or settings under which encoding processes are performed;
- "configurations" are the specific settings or parameters used during the encoding process;
- "elapsed time" is the duration taken for the encoding process to complete.

- "Most efficient" refers to configurations with the lowest average elapsed time and CPU usage;
- "Scenario" refers to the specific context or use case for the encoding;
- "Quality setting" refers to the level of quality (e.g., bitrate, resolution) for the encoded content.

- "Best average performance" is determined by the shortest average elapsed time for encoding;
- "Encoding configurations" are unique settings used to encode videos;
- "Scenarios" are specific use cases or situations where encoding configurations are applied.

- The performance score is calculated using a weighted sum: 0.4 for frames per second (fps), 0.3 for kilobits per second (kbs), and 0.3 for CPU usage;
- The top 3 configurations are first identified based on the average frames per second;
- The final configuration is selected based on the highest overall performance score.

